The dimension axiom states that for a single-point space *, the homology groups H_n(*) are isomorphic to a fixed group (the coefficient group) for n = 0, and trivial (zero) for n ≠ 0:
H_n(*) ≅ { G if n = 0, 0 otherwise }
Here, G is the coefficient group of the homology theory (e.g., G = ℤ for integer homology). This axiom ensures that the homology of a point is simple and provides a base case for computing homology groups of more complex spaces via techniques like the Mayer-Vietoris sequence.

